Subject: [sfraves]Did you go to the DirtyBird BBQ?

Wuts up all!!

Just wondering if any of you made it out to Golden
Gate Park for the DirtyBird BBQ?  That shit was dope,
I had a lot of fun.  We got there at like 3:30 and it
was a little sparse.  Grabbed some perfectly seasoned
tacos and a Redhawk, then proceeded to get down on the
dancefloor to some dope house.

By 4:30 it was packed!  I met so many cool people. 
It's been such a long time since I went to a party
like this and the vibe was fuckn awesome.

fable....

> bouncy stuff that i was diggin' & I danced out maybe the last 20 minutes
> of the club... It was kinda fun 'cause after Anu closed & Ray was fixing
> the decks & mixer up to like when we all ended up in the parking lot, lik=
e
> DrumCell & I kinda caught up on everything since we last hung out last
> year... So dope.. he always says somethiung inspiring to me whenever we
> talk & stuff... so that was kinda CooL...
>

> to get in... so i jsut went to AllStar on 5th for a donut & coffee... ok.=

> adventurous, interesting, & some kinda strangeness in there too!  This

e

>

> dudes that clean up the trash around BART (Civic Center Station) & him & =
I

> the water people were coming to wet down the station like they do every
> morning & Thankfully they didn't!  But yeah... this guy waws hella funny =
&

> Brooklyn, NY, but now so much... then he told me he was German & then it

> yeah.... this guy, Peter, was just heeeeeeeella fuckin' funny!!!
>
> Then I went down in the lower part by the stairs towards the entrance to
> BART & the Escalators... some dude was there I thoght fixing it... but he
> cleaned it & I've never seen an escalator look that clean, I wanted to
> like lick it... anywaze... his name is Rob, he lives in Portland w/ his
> family & has 3 jobs... an escalator cleaner, an elevator parts person, & =
a
> lumberjack... I guess he's the best Elevator cleaner for the City to get

n

> & luckily I got back to BART just as the 1st train to the East Bay pulled

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Question about "Wicked Mayhem"

That's funny, because I always thought Wicked Mayhem lifted 
their name from Yarrow's thing (Mystical Mayhem).

Wicked != Wicked Mayhem || Mystical Mayhem != Wicked Mayhem || 
(Wicked + Mystical Mayhem) != Wicked Mayhem

I met a couple of them, AFAICT they're a group of 30-something 
filipino/asians I haven't seen around before. This is their 
2nd (or 3rd?) year throwing parties. IMHO their 
lineups/production values/venues are pretty decent, although 
the parties themselves aren't exactly my taste.

So you're looking for work, but don't care if you get a job in the line
of work you're looking for?  Do you not need to work for a living or is
there some other reason you feel you have the luxury of not pursuing
any and all opportunities for employment or was there some difference?

Not knowing you, the only feedback I'd have is that adult content sites
are often the most professional organizations to work with.  They know
what they do and they do it; there's plenty of money to actually resource
key projects; people are expected to deliver, but there's no myth that
one needs to sacrifice personal life for career.

If you think that saying you applied to a pr0n site will make you seem
cooler, it seems just as likely the youngins will actually decide that
you are an even creepier an old guy. :P  I really don't think that's a good
reason to apply for a job.  OTOH, if you want and need a job and this
one is at all suited to your skills and abilities, and you can deal with
the fact that you'll be working for a pr0n company, go for it: it's
good money, reasonable hours and expectations.


-R.

Well, you said you're looking for work as a web developer, penthouse
is hiring web developers.  If safeway down the street is going to have
web developer positions then cool, otherwise they really don't compare.

> for it, i don't know how i'd feel about commuting to palo alto.   

>From SF?  annoying drive but not bad, better than the reverse.
Do you have a car that gets at least 30MPG?  or live near caltrain?

> we'll see.  i've actually applied for 50-60 jobs in the last month,  
> so it's not like I'm not trying.
> 
> c'mon, laugh.  this kind of a job does have to make you giggle just a

I really don't see why I would.  The only reason I didn't apply at
kink.com last year was that I found another job about the same time
as they caught my attention.  This is high tech, there's no way to
know when it's going to end so good jobs with good companies having
bright futures is a situation well worth pursuing.  Something like
Penthouse is going to have a steady revenue stream and probably
present you with good long term career options, and maybe even
other options if you find you want to change directions later.

I mean, it's not like you found a web development job with La Pequena.

Actually yeah, I've definitely heard harder.  I think it's a combo that
he's been going international more (he did a similar set in Guadelajara
earlier in the month), and the crowd was only about half hardcore heads.
We got some of the "fuck 1015" crowd, and some other folks who walked in
off the street, too, plus he was about at the comfortable limits of the
sound system.  When Cesare vs Disorder played back in March, he pushed
it and got harder bass, but the bottles were starting to rattle off the
bar, not a good scene.  Never scare your bar staff. :)

Still, I loved his track selection, and it was pretty hard for what
folks are used to hearing at Anu.  Between him and Forest, I felt a
little sorry for Developer, who didn't do anything wrong; I just stuck
him in between 2 unbelievable acts.  Anyway, as a total party I'm just
thrilled with how everything turned out.  Huge thanks to everyone who
made it out, the crowd was the best we've gotten yet, and I saw way
more of the list than I expected.  I shall endeavor to keep delivering
the awesomeness as long as folks want it. :)  Heck, I might even start
a 2nd party if I can work out the details (venue, system, visuals, etc).



-Ray

Subject: [sfraves] Looking for work

Seeing Deepfog's post pushed me in to speaking of my own need for new 
income.  As on old fart, I've got quite a bit of software development 
experience, covering a wide range of areas.  Five years ago, working for 
a not so ethical company (back when the question was, "Still in 
business?  Is it Pr0n or Spam?"), I was driven to escape that reality. 
So I went to work for myself, developing a number of my own web 
properties (some of which I've pointed out here, 
http://www.joketribe.com for instance, and I've got properties dealing 
with Affiliate Marketing, Automobile Purchasing/Safety/Maintenance, 
iPods (http://www.ipod24x7.com), wii's (http://www.wii24x7.com) (I sense 
a trend)) as well as taking the freelance gigs as I was able to get 
them.  Next thing I have lined up is a online store for a local handmade 
soap maker (which is COMPLETELY in the realm of what I appreciate.)  But 
after that....

Working in the AJAX/Javascript realm these days, well versed in various 
Web APIs (eBay, Amazon, etc.), 8 years with the LAMP stack.

My resume is here:
http://kzsu.stanford.edu/~dougm/DougsRes.html

So, if you know of freelance gigs doing web dev. for the little guys, 
non-profit situations, or even development work for the bigger guys, as 
long as ethics are followed, I'd certainly appreciate hearing about it. 
My recent conservation of resources hasn't been so pleasing. :)

Thanks in advance!

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Looking for work

Got laid off myself back in late April and all I can say about the tech
market is that there are many jobs available but there are also many
candidates on the market, so companies are having a hard time trying to find
actual talent.

Took me about 6 weeks (twice as quick than last time) but I have three
companies making competing offers this week, so I'm pretty pysch'd. I
recommend contacting recruiters and tech head-hunters as I had more of them
contact me vs the actual companies themselves. I'm sure you know all the job
posting websites but these were the ones I hit everyday:

craigslist
indeed
dice
careerbuilder
linkedin
hotjobs
monster
jobfox (new one but cool)

Good luck on the hunt!

-Smithers

Subject: [sfraves] Looking for work


Seeing Deepfog's post pushed me in to speaking of my own need for new
income.  As on old fart, I've got quite a bit of software development
experience, covering a wide range of areas.  Five years ago, working for
a not so ethical company (back when the question was, "Still in
business?  Is it Pr0n or Spam?"), I was driven to escape that reality.
So I went to work for myself, developing a number of my own web
properties (some of which I've pointed out here,
http://www.joketribe.com for instance, and I've got properties dealing
with Affiliate Marketing, Automobile Purchasing/Safety/Maintenance,
iPods (http://www.ipod24x7.com), wii's (http://www.wii24x7.com) (I sense
a trend)) as well as taking the freelance gigs as I was able to get
them.  Next thing I have lined up is a online store for a local handmade
soap maker (which is COMPLETELY in the realm of what I appreciate.)  But
after that....

Working in the AJAX/Javascript realm these days, well versed in various
Web APIs (eBay, Amazon, etc.), 8 years with the LAMP stack.

My resume is here:
http://kzsu.stanford.edu/~dougm/DougsRes.html

So, if you know of freelance gigs doing web dev. for the little guys,
non-profit situations, or even development work for the bigger guys, as
long as ethics are followed, I'd certainly appreciate hearing about it.
My recent conservation of resources hasn't been so pleasing. :)

Thanks in advance!

Ah, good to know.  I've seen Penthouse postings every few months for the
last couple years, so I don't pay much attention anymore.

I did interview with friendfinder some years back, they claimed to be
quite interested in learning how to make a stable production environment,
how to create a code release process to reduce the bugs getting out onto
the public sites, etc.  They were also quite adamant that wanting such
and refusing to even consider any sort of code versioning system were
completely compatible.

I'd hope that the Penthouse parents are a little more open to thinking
about software development as a manageable flow...

options even when it's Cable's off week.  There's also LoveIt
Weds at Icon, but like Satellite, there's a door.  Also, the space
tends to feel more dead than more intimate spots like Anu and Shine.

Subject: [sfraves] bsp: Tomorrow! [KONTROL] 3-Year Anniversary warmup w/ SAMMY DEE (Perlon:Berlin)!!!

------=_Part_3003_9009583.1212622028657
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

I'm pinching myself...
It seems too good to be true...
Yet...shit!...it IS true!

Music lovers of San Francisco...

LET'S GET PERLONIZED!!!

Berlin's living legend rocking a 2.5 hour DJ set in the intimate basement of
the 222!


[KONTROL] presents:

SAMMY DEE (Perlon, Poker Flat, Hello?Repeat)

aka Half Hawaii (w/ Bruno Pronsato)
aka Pantytec (w/ Perlon founder Zip)
aka Schneider & Radecki (w/ Guido Schneider)

***exclusive SF appearance***


[KONTROL] DJs warmin' things up:

Nikola Baytala / Craig Kuna / Alland Byallo / Sammy D


opening "farewell" set by Berlin-bound:

James Bass (Bassaholics Anonymous)


live visuals by: Heroic Robot

________________________________________________

Thursday June 5th, 2008  //  222 Hyde, SF  //  9p-2am
$10 / no guestlist / 100 capacity / first come, first served
________________________________________________


*** THERE ARE NO PRESALES ***

Anyone who's been to 222 knows it's, shall we say,
"intimate".  With a maximum capacity of only 100, this
event is sure to pack out early. When we're full, we're full,
no matter how VIP you think you are.  Thus, we strongly
recommend arriving before 11:00pm to ensure entry.


 *** THERE IS NO GUESTLIST ***

Due to the small venue size we are asking that each and
every person through the door cough up their share to help
cover the fee, airfare, and accomodations for this top notch
talent!  The price was set at $10 each to just cover breaking
even. Thanks for understanding and pulling your weight to
allow this special event to occur with such short notice!

________________________________________________


Sammy Dee is truly one of the best in the business!

We're all in for a real treat.  See you tomorrow.   :)


-----> Greg and the [KONTROL] Crew

------=_Part_3003_9009583.1212622028657--

Saturday, June 7th, 2008

[ K O N T R O L ]

3 YEAR ANNIVERSARY

minimal techno + avant house
every 1st Saturday at The Endup


featuring from London via Berlin:

RADIO SLAVE

Rekids . Poker Flat . Get Physical

Matt Edwards is easily one of the most unique and important
artists in dance music today. Sure, he runs a label (Rekids),
has loads of aliases (Matthew E, Quiet Village, Sea Devils,
Rekid, Radio Slave) and produces hits of his own, but what
truly sets him apart is his ablity to reimagine the music of
others. The jaw-dropping list of artists he's remixed includes
Carl Craig, Kylie Minogue, New Order, Justice, Trentemoller,
UNKLE, Sasha, Tiga, Bob Sinclar, Slam, The Pet Shop Boys,
Clipse, Moby, Paul McCartney, and countless others. This
man has amazing records no one else has and an inimitable
style all his own. Listen and learn!


and from Stockholm via Berlin:

PAR GRINDVIK  ** live PA **

Drumcode . Spectral Sound . Stockholm LTD

P=E4r Grindvik has been an integral member of the Swedish
electronic scene since the 90's as record store owner,
label manager, producer and performer. His rigorous touring
schedule and well-received releases on Drumcode, Spectral
Sound, and his own Stockholm LTD have made him a
respected player on the international scene and prompted
his relocation, like so many before him, to the Mecca of
Minimal, Berlin, Germany. Hot on the heels of performances
at Miami's WMC and a main stage set at Detroit's Movement
Festival (DEMF), don't miss his driving yet intelligent live set
in one of only four US appearances!


plus special guest:

MONTY LUKE   ( mothership . demon days . xlr8r )

with resident DJs:

SAMMY D   ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
ALLAND BYALLO   ( nightlight . auralism . leibe*detail )
CRAIG KUNA   ( platform . esdjco )
NIKOLA BAYTALA   ( robsoul . junior boys own . s.w.a.t. )

RADIO SLAVE  (aka Rekid, Quiet Village, Matthew E)

No matter what sounds you profess to be your music of choice, chances are,
that at some point over the last five years, you will have got your rocks
off to Matt Edwards.

As Matthew E he fashions club-based, dancefloor slayers. Under that aegis
he's updated the classic Chi-town, jackin' sound beloved of house
aficionados and layered it with fractured funk, belligerent, oddball beats
and mechanical soul.

If Matthew E is all about the Saturday Night Fever, then, by contrast, Reki=
d
is the slower, more deliberate, rhythmical funk of the mid-week mayhem. Its
well-intentioned muscular intensity making it perfect soulful sustenance.

Quiet Village is something else all together. A collaboration with long-tim=
e
musical sparring partner Joel Martin (a vinyl freak, like Mr Edwards, who
works in esteemed auction house Christie's pop department), it's
sample-based music which veers from drawn out disco-not-disco delirium to
evocative, under-stated soundscapes.

Sea Devils - you keeping up at the back? =96 is undeniable electronic pop
brilliance. Working with Tom from Cagedbaby, it's the least niche of Matt's
projects and thanks to Sea Devils alluring pop dance grooves they'll no
doubt be shagging the upper reaches of the hit parade sometime soon.

Last, but by no means least etc, etc, etc, is Radio Slave. Perhaps Matt's
most instantly recognisable nom de guerre, thanks in part to his
inspirational melding of Kylie's Can't Get You Out Of My Head to New Order'=
s
Blue Monday, this is Matt's DJ moniker and the guise under which he
completes his incendiary remixes and re-edits.

However, before such sonic schizophrenia gets you calling for the men in
white coats, just feel the quality and consider Matt's legacy. Fired by the
first wave of acid house, Matt gained his musical spurs by partying to danc=
e
music that was just that: music you danced to, irrespective of tribal
factions.

This was the raison d'=EAtre he acknowledged when he took to the decks, fir=
st
at London's legendary Milk Bar in 1992, then onto the, then, recently opene=
d
Ministry Of Sound and then to parties across the country, most notably in
Wales =96 where he was a regular at free parties =96 and in Brighton, his h=
ome
since 1998.

His love of re-edits, dance music's oft-forgotten backbone, led Matt into
the studio himself. His own re-edits and remixes, such as the aforementione=
d
epoch-defining re-imagining for Ms Minogue, soon gave way to his own
productions and since the floodgates opened there's been no stopping the ma=
n
known as, erm, Matthew E, Quiet Village, Sea Devils, Rekid and Radio Slave.

He's released records for Skint, Soul Jazz, Classic, Whatever We Want, and
he's worked with fellow travellers, Belgium's The Glimmers. If Matt comes u=
p
with another two projects he'll have enough alter egos for every day of the
week.

Psychologists would probably have a field day with him; mercifully, we don'=
t
have to worry about any crisis of identity, we just get to keep on dancing.

http://www.rekids.com/

Radio Slave's discography:  <--- (OMG, CHECK THIS OUT!)
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Radio%20Slave

Radio Slave on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/rekid

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DmqybOHTuqNU

Radio Slave - Live @ Foundation, Minneapolis - 10.18.07
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Di4gVINu6xWY


____________________________________________________


PAR GRINDVIK

Enjoying life inspired by memories and music from the past, combining them
with the progressing sound of techno. P=E4r Grindvik is an artist that alwa=
ys
aims to compose music that keeps the aesthetics and underground culture
alive.

P=E4r Grindvik or his pseudonym The Hollow has been a core person of the
Swedish electronic scene since the nineties as record store-owner (Illegal
Stockholm), label manager and producer. He is a well established artist and
after many years of touring and releases on big name labels like Drumcode,
Spectral Sound and his own label Stockholm LTD, which he created and founde=
d
in 2002, he is now based in Berlin, Germany.

Stockholm LTD began as an outlet for singles and EPs from Swedish electroni=
c
artists with a focus on releasing timeless electronic music. Nowadays it's
much more, as each release tells its own story. Every inch of P=E4r's work,
including the label, artwork, release info and music, is wrapped with heart
and emotion, which keeps the sparkle and curiosity alive within the ever
changing adaptations of the artistic world.

Thus, P=E4r Grindvik is one of the most promising names around today and on=
e
of the most respected producers out there!


=3D=3D> LINKS:

P=E4r Grindvik's website:
http://www.stockholmltd.com

P=E4r Grindvik on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/grindvik

P=E4r Grindvik's discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/P%C3%A4r+Grindvik


=3D=3D> MUSIC:

P=E4r Grindvik - Live PA @ Spectral Sound Social, WMC 2008: (streaming @)
http://www.stockholmltd.com/

P=E4r Grindvik on Beatport:
https://www.beatport.com/en-US/html/content/artist/detail/13861/par_grindvi=
k


=3D=3D> VIDEO:

P=E4r Grindvik - Live @ BED, Drumcode Night, WMC 2008
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D-b4_QPC8Wyo

P=E4r Grindvik - Live @ Mimika, Torino - 05.19.08
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D_21D2xWC4-E


____________________________________________________


MONTY LUKE  (aka ML Tronik)

Monty Luke brings a funky, raw eclectic sound to the west coast techno
underground. Dubbed a favorite amongst local DJ's and 'those that know' for
years, Monty has continued to set the bar high for himself and his
listeners, melding his upfront, cut-up DJ mix style and electrifying
presence to dancefloors worldwide. He currently is resident DJ at Demon
Days, an event by Detroit legend and producer Carl Craig. The party takes
place in San Francisco 4 times each year and has had guests such as
Lindstrom and Lazy Fat People.

In 2002, Monty released "What U Feel," a collaboration between himself and
reclusive producer extraordinaire L. Ray Robinson under the moniker
Loopwreckas on the Imperial Dub label. Monty also has recorded with Stompy
Hi-Fi resident DJ Tasho and they have completed a two-track e.p. for Claude
Von Stroke's Mothership label entitled "Paranoid," Be on the lookout for
more solo productions as ML Tronik, in particular "The Diamond Boxx e.p."
which was co-produced in Detroit in 2006 with the help of legendary produce=
r
Carl Craig. A follow up to 'Paranoid' called "Personal Problems" will be ou=
t
on Mothership later in 2008.

He currently is resident DJ at Demon Days, a nationwide event which feature=
s
DJ sets by Detroit legend and producer Carl Craig. The party takes place in
San Francisco 4 times each year and has had guests such as Lindstrom and
Lazy Fat People.

In 2008, Monty remains focused on bringing that raw, eclectic electronic
jack music to the world through both his DJ sets, and original productions.
The future is now. Go get some No-Doze!


=3D=3D> LINKS:

Monty Luke's website:
http://www.mltronik.com

Monty Luke on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/mltronik


=3D=3D> MUSIC:

Monty Luke - XLR8R Bubble Metropolis Mix 005  (1 hr. 125MB, 320kbps)
http://www.mltronik.com/music07/BubbleMetropolisPodcastMix5v2Master.mp3

[ K O N T R O L ]

3 YEAR ANNIVERSARY

minimal techno + avant house
every 1st Saturday at The Endup


featuring from London via Berlin:

RADIO SLAVE

Rekids . Poker Flat . Get Physical

Matt Edwards is easily one of the most unique and important
artists in dance music today. Sure, he runs a label (Rekids),
has loads of aliases (Matthew E, Quiet Village, Sea Devils,
Rekid, Radio Slave) and produces hits of his own, but what
truly sets him apart is his ablity to reimagine the music of
others. The jaw-dropping list of artists he's remixed includes
Carl Craig, Kylie Minogue, New Order, Justice, Trentemoller,
UNKLE, Sasha, Tiga, Bob Sinclar, Slam, The Pet Shop Boys,
Clipse, Moby, Paul McCartney, and countless others. This
man has amazing records no one else has and an inimitable
style all his own. Listen and learn!


and from Stockholm via Berlin:

PAR GRINDVIK  ** live PA **

Drumcode . Spectral Sound . Stockholm LTD

P=E4r Grindvik has been an integral member of the Swedish
electronic scene since the 90's as record store owner,
label manager, producer and performer. His rigorous touring
schedule and well-received releases on Drumcode, Spectral
Sound, and his own Stockholm LTD have made him a
respected player on the international scene and prompted
his relocation, like so many before him, to the Mecca of
Minimal, Berlin, Germany. Hot on the heels of performances
at Miami's WMC and a main stage set at Detroit's Movement
Festival (DEMF), don't miss his driving yet intelligent live set
in one of only four US appearances!


plus special guest:

MONTY LUKE   ( mothership . demon days . xlr8r )

____________________________________________________


RADIO SLAVE  (aka Rekid, Quiet Village, Matthew E)

No matter what sounds you profess to be your music of choice, chances are,
that at some point over the last five years, you will have got your rocks
off to Matt Edwards.

As Matthew E he fashions club-based, dancefloor slayers. Under that aegis
he's updated the classic Chi-town, jackin' sound beloved of house
aficionados and layered it with fractured funk, belligerent, oddball beats
and mechanical soul.

If Matthew E is all about the Saturday Night Fever, then, by contrast, Reki=
d
is the slower, more deliberate, rhythmical funk of the mid-week mayhem. Its
well-intentioned muscular intensity making it perfect soulful sustenance.

Quiet Village is something else all together. A collaboration with long-tim=
e
musical sparring partner Joel Martin (a vinyl freak, like Mr Edwards, who
works in esteemed auction house Christie's pop department), it's
sample-based music which veers from drawn out disco-not-disco delirium to
evocative, under-stated soundscapes.

Sea Devils - you keeping up at the back? =96 is undeniable electronic pop
brilliance. Working with Tom from Cagedbaby, it's the least niche of Matt's
projects and thanks to Sea Devils alluring pop dance grooves they'll no
doubt be shagging the upper reaches of the hit parade sometime soon.

Last, but by no means least etc, etc, etc, is Radio Slave. Perhaps Matt's
most instantly recognisable nom de guerre, thanks in part to his
inspirational melding of Kylie's Can't Get You Out Of My Head to New Order'=
s
Blue Monday, this is Matt's DJ moniker and the guise under which he
completes his incendiary remixes and re-edits.

However, before such sonic schizophrenia gets you calling for the men in
white coats, just feel the quality and consider Matt's legacy. Fired by the
first wave of acid house, Matt gained his musical spurs by partying to danc=
e
music that was just that: music you danced to, irrespective of tribal
factions.

This was the raison d'=EAtre he acknowledged when he took to the decks, fir=
st
at London's legendary Milk Bar in 1992, then onto the, then, recently opene=
d
Ministry Of Sound and then to parties across the country, most notably in
Wales =96 where he was a regular at free parties =96 and in Brighton, his h=
ome
since 1998.

His love of re-edits, dance music's oft-forgotten backbone, led Matt into
the studio himself. His own re-edits and remixes, such as the aforementione=
d
epoch-defining re-imagining for Ms Minogue, soon gave way to his own
productions and since the floodgates opened there's been no stopping the ma=
n
known as, erm, Matthew E, Quiet Village, Sea Devils, Rekid and Radio Slave.

He's released records for Skint, Soul Jazz, Classic, Whatever We Want, and
he's worked with fellow travellers, Belgium's The Glimmers. If Matt comes u=
p
with another two projects he'll have enough alter egos for every day of the
week.

Psychologists would probably have a field day with him; mercifully, we don'=
t
have to worry about any crisis of identity, we just get to keep on dancing.

____________________________________________________


PAR GRINDVIK

Enjoying life inspired by memories and music from the past, combining them
with the progressing sound of techno. P=E4r Grindvik is an artist that alwa=
ys
aims to compose music that keeps the aesthetics and underground culture
alive.

P=E4r Grindvik or his pseudonym The Hollow has been a core person of the
Swedish electronic scene since the nineties as record store-owner (Illegal
Stockholm), label manager and producer. He is a well established artist and
after many years of touring and releases on big name labels like Drumcode,
Spectral Sound and his own label Stockholm LTD, which he created and founde=
d
in 2002, he is now based in Berlin, Germany.

Stockholm LTD began as an outlet for singles and EPs from Swedish electroni=
c
artists with a focus on releasing timeless electronic music. Nowadays it's
much more, as each release tells its own story. Every inch of P=E4r's work,
including the label, artwork, release info and music, is wrapped with heart
and emotion, which keeps the sparkle and curiosity alive within the ever
changing adaptations of the artistic world.

Thus, P=E4r Grindvik is one of the most promising names around today and on=
e
of the most respected producers out there!

____________________________________________________


MONTY LUKE  (aka ML Tronik)

Monty Luke brings a funky, raw eclectic sound to the west coast techno
underground. Dubbed a favorite amongst local DJ's and 'those that know' for
years, Monty has continued to set the bar high for himself and his
listeners, melding his upfront, cut-up DJ mix style and electrifying
presence to dancefloors worldwide. He currently is resident DJ at Demon
Days, an event by Detroit legend and producer Carl Craig. The party takes
place in San Francisco 4 times each year and has had guests such as
Lindstrom and Lazy Fat People.

In 2002, Monty released "What U Feel," a collaboration between himself and
reclusive producer extraordinaire L. Ray Robinson under the moniker
Loopwreckas on the Imperial Dub label. Monty also has recorded with Stompy
Hi-Fi resident DJ Tasho and they have completed a two-track e.p. for Claude
Von Stroke's Mothership label entitled "Paranoid," Be on the lookout for
more solo productions as ML Tronik, in particular "The Diamond Boxx e.p."
which was co-produced in Detroit in 2006 with the help of legendary produce=
r
Carl Craig. A follow up to 'Paranoid' called "Personal Problems" will be ou=
t
on Mothership later in 2008.

He currently is resident DJ at Demon Days, a nationwide event which feature=
s
DJ sets by Detroit legend and producer Carl Craig. The party takes place in
San Francisco 4 times each year and has had guests such as Lindstrom and
Lazy Fat People.
I
In 2008, Monty remains focused on bringing that raw, eclectic electronic
jack music to the world through both his DJ sets, and original productions.
The future is now. Go get some No-Doze!

Subject: [sfraves] Where are you, my fellow old ravers?

--Boundary_(ID_K/NJ/JopRYUlCNhQ16WM6A)
Content-type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII; format=flowed; delsp=yes
Content-transfer-encoding: 7BIT


Where are you, my fellow old ravers?

     * Rafael Behr
     * The Observer,
     * Sunday June 8 2008
     * Article history

There isn't much adolescent idealism on a gym treadmill. I see  
grimaces of fellow thirty-somethings atoning for their sedentary  
lifestyles. The soundtrack to this purgatory is techno. Relentless and  
urgent, it is meant to spur people on. Ung-cha, ung-cha, ung-cha.  
Must. Work. Harder.

Electronic dance music is part of Britain's audio furniture. It  
reverberates in bars and clubs, is the soundtrack to TV shows, adverts  
and radio jingles. And it always plays in gyms. It was there that I  
found myself pondering, as I hurtled on the spot, the peculiar fact  
that this music was once illicit. Those bangs and bleeps are  
descendants of the music I used to know, and love, as rave, which was  
controversial enough to be singled out for statutory censure.

Twenty years ago, dance music was the property of a subculture, a  
mostly hedonistic but implicitly political movement, anti-materialist,  
collectivist, draping itself in the flowery colours of 60s hippy  
revival. The summer of 1988 was dubbed the 'Second Summer of Love'. Or  
was it 1989? No one is sure, evidence of how incoherent it all was.

But the government certainly thought it dangerous. In 1994, the  
Criminal Justice and Public Order Act made it illegal for people to  
gather in fields and dance to music 'characterised by the emission of  
a sequence of repetitive beats'.

Britain didn't invent house and techno, but it was here that, through  
raves, dance culture induced a hysterical conservative backlash. That  
is largely because of the drugs. Raving accompanied an explosion in  
the use of ecstasy. But it also represented, like punk, a reaction  
against the political status quo. Rave was youth culture's  
counterpoint to High Thatcherism.

Eventually, the whole thing dissolved. The Criminal Justice Act pushed  
dance music (and drugs) into nightclubs. The record industry, as  
always, captured the trend and milked it. By 1997, New Labour was  
using D:Ream's 'Things Can Only Get Better' (imitation rave) as its  
anthem.

There is nothing unusual about subcultures turning mainstream. But  
when the punks combed their hair and got jobs at least the musical  
aesthetic stayed radical. When the original flower-power generation  
grew up, they changed the world.

But while the aesthetics of the 80s dance revolution colonised popular  
culture, the political consequence was tiny. Labour didn't need votes  
from disgruntled ravers to win in 1997.

Some nostalgists argue that rave was vital to the growth of  
environmentalism or that protests against the Criminal Justice Act  
turned people on to the techniques of direct action. But none of those  
things is now associated with the music.

Imagine a formula for calculating the impact of a subversive youth  
culture. It would factor in the scale of moral panic, the  
effectiveness of subsequent hijacking by fashion and music industries  
and changes in values that were smuggled into the mainstream. Rave  
would come out as the biggest sell-out ever. Consumerism won hands down.

The 20th anniversary of the 'Second Summer of Love' is coming and  
where are all the ravers? Some have surely penetrated the  
establishment. There must be barristers, bankers, even ministers among  
them. The repetitive beats are everywhere, but the rave generation is  
invisible. We pound out our hippy idealism on the treadmill.

http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2008/jun/08/2/print





Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

The US is:  "...a nation of 200 million used-car salesmen with all the  
money we need to buy guns and no qualms about killing anybody else in  
the world who tries to make us uncomfortable."
-Hunter S. Thompson

"Friend, hope for the truth while you are alive.  Jump into experience  
while you are alive!  What you call "salvation" belongs to the time  
before death.  If you don't break your ropes while you are alive, do  
you think ghosts will do it after?"
-Kabir





--Boundary_(ID_K/NJ/JopRYUlCNhQ16WM6A)--

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Apple Announces Faster, Cheaper iPhone

--0-1575788577-1213050648=:53746
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

http://money.cnn.com/2008/06/09/technology/applekeynote.fortune/index.htm?cnn=yes

NEW YORK (Fortune) -- Apple announced on Monday a much faster iPhone that's half the price of the current model.
The news is expected to address one of the biggest complaints about the hugely popular iPhone: That its network is too slow. CEO Steve Jobs said the new iPhone, which is based on 3G technology, is 36% faster than top rival Nokia's N95 smartphone.
As Fortune.com first reported, the new 8-gigabyte iPhone will cost $199 and a 16-gigabyte version will cost $299. Jobs says the new iPhone will be available worldwide starting July 11. It will allow up to six hours of Web browsing and five hours of talk time. 
Jobs announced the 3G iPhone, which had been rumored for months, at the company's annual World Wide Developers conference in San Francisco.
Apple shares fell 4% after the iPhone announcement, as some investors were left wanting more from the gadget maker. The stock had been up 55% in the past three months on heightened expectations for a radically improved iPhone and the possibility of other product launches.
While the price cut was good news for consumers, U.S. iPhone partner AT&T said it would feel the pinch of having to lay out a subsidy for the new phone. In a press release late Monday, AT&T said the iPhone costs will cut adjusted earnings by about 11 cents this year and next.
AT&T's exclusive iPhone partnership also calls for the company to share as much as 24% of its monthly iPhone service revenue with Apple. 
During the show, Jobs also introduced a slew of new applications for the iPhone, including a wireless system that automatically forwards e-mail to other devices, a friend-finding service called Loopt and mobile blogging software from TypePad.
Other new applications for the iPhone include a service from MLB.com that provides a live scoreboard of major league games, and music-making software, called Cow Terry, for creating songs on the phone.
The new iPhone applications are aimed at boosting revenue from data services. Wireless companies increasingly are looking to these services to offset slowing growth in mobile phone sales. Apple, for instance, will charge $99 a year for its new MobileMe service, which sends e-mail, contact and calendar updates to a user's devices.
The new services drew plenty of 'oohs' and 'aahs' from the 5,200 attendees at Apple's developers conference. But the main attraction was the 3G iPhone. 
Since the original iPhone was introduced nearly a year ago, Apple (AAPL, Fortune 500) has sold 6 million handsets, Jobs said Monday. The company has set a goal of selling 10 million handsets worldwide this year.
But iPhone users have complained loudly about the cumbersome EDGE network, which is operated by AT&T (T, Fortune 500), the exclusive seller of the iPhone in the United States.
Jobs kicked off the conference by talking about the iPhone for business users, a lucrative market dominated by rival Research in Motion (RIMM). He said that the iPhone now works with Microsoft's Exchange office server systems - a key feature if the iPhone hopes to crack the BlackBerry's lock on working professionals.
Jobs also said that 35% of the Fortune 500 has participated in a beta program for business applications for the iPhone. 
Also, Jobs announced that the new version of the Mac operating system OS X is called "Snow Leopard."

NEW YORK (Fortune) -- Apple announced on Monday a much faster iPhone that's half the price of the current model.
The news is expected to address one of the biggest complaints about the hugely popular iPhone: That its network is too slow. CEO Steve Jobs said the new iPhone, which is based on 3G technology, is 36% faster than top rival Nokia's N95 smartphone.

Jobs announced the 3G iPhone, which had been rumored for months, at the company's annual World Wide Developers conference in San Francisco.
Apple shares fell 4% after the iPhone announcement, as some investors were left wanting more from the gadget maker. The stock had been up 55% in the past three months on heightened expectations for a radically improved iPhone and the possibility of other product launches.
While the price cut was good news for consumers, U.S. iPhone partner AT&T said it would feel the pinch of having to lay out a subsidy for the new phone. In a press release late Monday, AT&T said the iPhone costs will cut adjusted earnings by about 11 cents this year and next.
AT&T's exclusive iPhone partnership also calls for the company to share as much as 24% of its monthly iPhone service revenue with Apple. 
During the show, Jobs also introduced a slew of new applications for the iPhone, including a wireless system that automatically forwards e-mail to other devices, a friend-finding service called Loopt and mobile blogging software from TypePad.
Other new applications for the iPhone include a service from MLB.com that provides a live scoreboard of major league games, and music-making software, called Cow Terry, for creating songs on the phone.
The new iPhone applications are aimed at boosting revenue from data services. Wireless companies increasingly are looking to these services to offset slowing growth in mobile phone sales. Apple, for instance, will charge $99 a year for its new MobileMe service, which sends e-mail, contact and calendar updates to a user's devices.
The new services drew plenty of 'oohs' and 'aahs' from the 5,200 attendees at Apple's developers conference. But the main attraction was the 3G iPhone. 
Since the original iPhone was introduced nearly a year ago, Apple (AAPL, Fortune 500) has sold 6 million handsets, Jobs said Monday. The company has set a goal of selling 10 million handsets worldwide this year.
But iPhone users have complained loudly about the cumbersome EDGE network, which is operated by AT&T (T, Fortune 500), the exclusive seller of the iPhone in the United States.

He said that the iPhone now works with Microsoft's Exchange office server systems - a key feature if the iPhone hopes to crack the BlackBerry's lock on working professionals.

Also, Jobs announced that the new version of the Mac operating system OS X is called "Snow Leopard."

Subject: [sfraves] CODA folks, and Seventh Swami on KZSU tomorrow (Thur.) morning!!

We've got a BIG morning in store for you tomorrow on KZSU.  It all 
starts with The Eclektronic Groove at 6a Pacific time, and runs through 
An Epiphany Of Sound until Noon.  This week we'll be featuring 5 
seperate folks in control of the beats.

First off is Holt, with a live mix for you from 6a-8a.  Check out his 
place on the web at http://hsomusic.com/

He'll be followed up by The Ambient Mafia's very own Seventh Swami from 
8a-9a, taking you from downtempo to midtempo to glitch and dubstep 
(hoping he can squeeze it all in one hour! :) )  He bridges the gap 
between "Live PA" and "Mashup DJ" in his performances by bringing 
together classic DJ techniques with glitchy effects, live sampling and 
on-the-spot remixing.  I'm expecting him to bring you a set that is 
spiritually uplifiting, original and thought-provoking.  The same sort 
of set that I'm expecting he'll bring the folks you partake in the 8 Yr. 
Anniversary of Stilldream.  (See http://www.stilldream.org for all the 
details!  I've had an amazing time all the past years that I've gone, 
and I'll be on the decks again this year BTW.)

At 9, we swing into An Epiphany Of Sound mode with 3 seperate folks who 
will be playing at the CODA Love Fest Float benefit party this weekend; 
Jason Knight, Ron/e, and Jeff Richmond.

Jason Knight is a 15 year musical veteran, bringing a wide range of 
sounds from Ambient/Downtempo, to Progressive House, Tech Trance and 
Trance, with 6 releases under his belt.  (Check him out at 
http://www.djjasonknight.com/)

Ron/e and Jeff Richmond are two more CODA residents (check them all out 
at http://codasf.com/music.html.)  Ron/e is part of the crew that 
brought you the Deep End and is also a resident at FiX.  Jeff Richmond 
is part of the crew that brought you the wonderful Aranji parties, and 
he loves to expand our consciousness with his brand of funky techno and 
house.

All I can say is look out!!  This is going to go down in the record 
books. ;)

All you need to do is tune in to 90.1 FM in the bay area, or listen 
online at http://kzsulive.stanford.edu (KZSU is also in the iTunes radio 
directory.)  It all starts at 6a Pacific Time, so set your alarm clocks!

Peace all!

Subject: [sfraves] (nrr) QOD (Mon)

--

I began a recent presentation before a large group of cattle producers  
(R-CALFUSA) by showing a paper dollar bill and a silver coin. The  
words ?one dollar? is inscribed on both the coin and the paper, yet  
the paper dollar will only pay for about one quart of gasoline at  
today?s prices, while the silver dollar will pay for well over five  
gallons. I explained to my audience that consumer prices are not high  
? the paper dollar has lost most of its value. It makes no difference  
how high the price of gasoline goes, a silver dollar will continue to  
buy gas for 20 cents a gallon, exactly the price gas was during the  
Great Depression. Based on 1940 prices, a paper dollar is worth about  
two pennies.

- Derry Brownfield

Source:  News With Views, SILVER, GOLD AND THE IRS,  
http://www.newswithviews.com/brownfield/brownfield67.htm

From: "Chelsea Faith" <chelcfaith@gmail.com>
To: SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>, def-announce@defsf.com
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: multipart/alternative; 
	boundary="----=_Part_11150_12125317.1213637936134"
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] From the DEF vaults... LPSF & Love Machine, 2004

------=_Part_11150_12125317.1213637936134
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

I was digging up some old files on a computer I haven't used in a few years,
and I found some videos of DEF's float in Love Parade 2004, as well as the
Love Machine afterparty held at the Drum Machine Museum / Infinite Kaos
space.
Early in the day, before the parade had started moving, we met a Dutch
couple, Brenda and Alex, who had come all the way out from Rotterdam to
check out the parade.  Brenda was a photographer, and Alex was a techno DJ
who brought his records along with him in hopes of spinning on one of the
floats. Our float was one of the smallest, but it was the only one playing
techno, so he came over and introduced himself to us and asked if there was
an open slot. When I scheduled the lineup for our float, I left an hour
free, so that when we inevitably fell behind schedule, I wouldn't have to
cut any DJs short.  I seriously doubted that we'd have any extra time, but I
told Alex that if we did, I'd let him play on our float later in the
evening. Amazingly, everything went off with no problems or delays, and we
were totally on schedule. At 6pm, I gave him the decks, and he threw down a
set of hard, hard, HARD techno, and totally rocked our socks. It was
definitely one of the highlights of the DEF float.  Afterwards, we brought
Alex and Brenda along to the Love Machine afterparty, where Sean was DJing.
 It was a pretty epic party - still one of my favorite events in recent
memory. A week or two later, Brenda emailed me the videos she took from the
parade and the afterparty.  I thought they were long lost, but now that
they've turned up I thought I'd share them with you guys...

The DEF Float:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rASBgagBIiM
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vGfiwtHAGJk

Love Machine:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YoBBF0WWaFs


Love Chelsea

Historical price of oil, dating back to 1949:
http://inflationdata.com/inflation/Inflation_Rate/Historical_Oil_Prices_Table.asp

Historical price of silver, dating back to 1792:
http://www.kitco.com/scripts/hist_charts/yearly_graphs.plx

In 1946, the price of silver was 86 cents an ounce; oil was $1.63/bbl.
In 1999, the price of silver was $5.28 an ounce; oil was $16.56/bbl.

Shrug.

Damon

Chelsea Faith wrote:
> I was digging up some old files on a computer I haven't used in a few
> years,
> and I found some videos of DEF's float in Love Parade 2004, as well as the
> Love Machine afterparty held at the Drum Machine Museum / Infinite Kaos
> space.
> Early in the day, before the parade had started moving, we met a Dutch
> couple, Brenda and Alex, who had come all the way out from Rotterdam to
> check out the parade.  Brenda was a photographer, and Alex was a techno DJ
> who brought his records along with him in hopes of spinning on one of the
> floats. Our float was one of the smallest, but it was the only one playing
> techno, so he came over and introduced himself to us and asked if there
> was
> an open slot. When I scheduled the lineup for our float, I left an hour
> free, so that when we inevitably fell behind schedule, I wouldn't have to
> cut any DJs short.  I seriously doubted that we'd have any extra time, but
> I
> told Alex that if we did, I'd let him play on our float later in the
> evening. Amazingly, everything went off with no problems or delays, and we
> were totally on schedule. At 6pm, I gave him the decks, and he threw down
> a
> set of hard, hard, HARD techno, and totally rocked our socks. It was
> definitely one of the highlights of the DEF float.  Afterwards, we brought
> Alex and Brenda along to the Love Machine afterparty, where Sean was
> DJing.
>  It was a pretty epic party - still one of my favorite events in recent
> memory. A week or two later, Brenda emailed me the videos she took from
> the
> parade and the afterparty.  I thought they were long lost, but now that
> they've turned up I thought I'd share them with you guys...
>
> The DEF Float:
> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rASBgagBIiM
> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vGfiwtHAGJk
>
> Love Machine:
> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YoBBF0WWaFs

> Love Chelsea

Whether you call them agents of The Ambient Mafia, or mistakenly identify a couple of them as Pandas, you owe it to yourself to hear their clarion call.

Sixty4K (We Are Not Pandas, Ambient Mafia)
Hickory (We Are Not Pandas, Ambient Mafia)
Squelchy (Ambient Mafia)

And DPR Resident, yours truly:
George Cochrane (Drop Music, Amenti Music, The Fingermonsters)

222 Hyde (@ Turk)
San Frandisco

7pm-11pm, and stay after for No Fucking Requests Ever!

Cheers,
-GC

Amp was pretty major for me too. As a young teenager, this was my
introduction to electronic music.  "These bands have no lead singers... and
the videos are CRAZY! What *is* this???"  I tried to get my girlfriends from
school to stay up late and watch it with me, but they weren't very
enthusiastic.  I specifically remember writing about it in my diary at the
time - "My friends want me to come to the Third Eye Blind concert with them,
but I'm really starting to get into techno..."   Ha!
I have many more episodes coming, stay tuned!

-CH

 Hello again, SFRavers.

First off, we at [KONTROL] all wanted to say a heartfelt thank you to each
and every one of you who came out to help us celebrate our third anniversary
on June 7th. The vibe was thick, the music was spot on, and the Endup was
hoppin'!  Holy cripes, have you ever even seen it that crazy in there
before?  Wow.  Thanks again for three incredible years, everyone. We do it
for you, and we certainly couldn't have done it without you!

Next, we want to tell you about what's sure to be a very fun show happening
tomorrow (Wednesday) night. MVP Entertainment and Love It! Wednesdays are
hosting the [KONTROL] DJ crew (minus Craig Kuna, who's in Europe at the
moment) in a one-night-only whizbanger at the intimate Icon Lounge. As much
as we love the Endup, sometimes it's nice to mix it up and see your
favorites play somewhere new, and Icon will definitely scratch that itch.
Come check out the boys droppin' their freshest wax alongside Love It!
resident Mikey Tello and enjoy a fine adult beverage or three with us!

Full details, address, etc. right here:
http://i77.photobucket.com/albums/j78/tellomatic/LOVEIT_KONTROL_PosterWeb.jpg

0900-1030 Michael Tello

Subject: [sfraves] decibel festival - submissions wanted


just wanted to encourage my loved sf friends to consider coming up north
for a truly amazing/worthwhile event. they're also seeking submissions
from people around the world. this got posted to a local list and i
figured i'd forward it :)


 *5th ANNUAL DECIBEL FESTIVAL DATES ANNOUNCED: SEPT 25 – 28, 2008*

The fifth annual Decibel Festival will again submerse Seattle in the broad
spectrum of
electronic music and its surrounding cultural elements. Since its inception
in 2003, Decibel has booked over 400 acts, culminating in the biggest
edition yet this fall. Following the success and critical acclaim of
previous editions, the festival will once again assemble a diverse selection
of international talent designed to stimulate its audience on multiple
levels. The lineup will feature artists at the forefront of electronic music
production, alongside exciting visual art performances and installations.
With this landmark anniversary, Decibel will feature surprises and return
favorites. Previous highlights over the years include: Richie Hawtin,
Trentemoller, Diplo, Boys Noize, Green Velvet, Switch, Monolake, Autechre,
Justice, Derrick May, Modeselektor, Gui Boratto, Matmos, Simian Mobile
Disco, Robin Guthrie & Harold Budd, Ellen Allien, Fennesz, Murcof, Apparat,
The Field, Isolee, John Tejada, Speedy J, Michael Mayer, Chris DeLuca vs.
Phon.o, Stars Of The Lid, Matthew Dear, Nortec Collective, Akufen, Tim
Hecker, Claude VonStroke, Sascha Funke, Styrofoam, Lusine, Jeff Samuel, The
Dead Texan, Smash TV, Marcus Nikolai, Vladislav Delay, T.Raumschmiere,
Loscil, Robert Babicz, Christopher Willits, Kangding Ray and Deadbeat.

*SUSTAINABILITY
IN THE ARTS* Seattle is one of the top green cities in the U.S., reflecting
the increasing global need for positive environmental impact. Decibel will
reflect this sustainability focus throughout its programming, hotel and
transportation partners, sponsors, educational outreach and other
components.

*CALL FOR SUBMISSIONS* Seattle's Decibel Festival returns in
2008 with an edition that will be more extensive and stimulating than ever.
We are currently seeking film, video and animated works to present during
OPTICAL 2008. Our theme this year is sustainability in the arts. We
encourage artists worldwide to submit their works for consideration. OPTICAL
covers multimedia performances, short films, animation, and other
cutting-edge visual work by some of today's most provocative artists. Past
highlights include audio/video performances by Ryoichi Kurokawa, Speedy J
w/Scott Pagano, Richard Chartier and Randy Jones. Please visit our website
for more information on how to submit your works.

*HOTEL PARTNERS* All
transportation and lodging partners this year feature ways to reduce
visitors' carbon footprints and ease their stay while in Seattle. They each
offer eco-friendly rooms while also providing comfort and a good night (or
morning) rest. These hotels are offering discounts to Decibel attendants:
Best Western Executive Inn: 206.448.9444
Best Western Loyal Inn: 206.682.0200
The Eight Avenue Inn: 206.233.0185

(kim's note - http://www.couchsurfing.com is a great alternative place to
find free places to stay if you don't mind sleeping at somebody's house)
:)

*ABOUT DECIBEL FESTIVAL* Founded in 2003,
Seattle's Decibel Festival (http://www.dbfestival.com) bridges the gap
between technology and creativity through visual art, workshops, panel
discussions and cutting-edge electronic music performances. By assembling
a diverse selection of international talent, Decibel Festival provides a
forum for musicians, industry professionals and educators alike. The 5th
Annual
Decibel International Festival of Electronic Music, Visual Art and New Media
is scheduled for September 25 through September 28, 2008.

From: Apollo <djapollo2k@mac.com>

Date: Tue, 17 Jun 2008 19:53:06 -0700

Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  some personal stuff

--Boundary_(ID_+MzU+mY3hQPNQ+cOVRwNVQ)
Content-type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII; format=flowed; delsp=yes
Content-transfer-encoding: 7BIT

I haven't posted to this list as much as I used to.  Today marks a  
year since I left hospital after a life and death struggle with spinal  
meningitis that left me unable to walk among other things.  Months  
more lying in a hospital bed at home struggling to relearn walking.   
Lots of time to think about things like the brevity of life and the  
primacy of family and friends.  Love while you can.

I haven't been out and about much and have become a bit of a recluse.   
Me, a believer in the life giving force of social, tribal dancing.  I  
so hope I can experience the ecstasy of the dancefloor once again!!

Then I learned of my daughter's tragic death.  Amoret was my only  
child. News came on Wednesday last week;  she apparently died of a  
heroin overdose at a party on June 1st and her body lay in the Tucson  
morgue unclaimed until last Wed.  So I have been living terrible pain  
and darkness the past few days.

So, finally a bright spot...today Joey, my partner of 30 years, and I  
got married!!!

We had not planned to, especially in the middle of this grieving.  I  
made an appointment to get a marriage license as soon as I heard the  
CA supreme court ruling.  We got a slot for the first full day of  
issuance.  We did not expect to marry.

But we had that appointment and no possibility of getting another one  
for at least a couple of weeks so we went into SF City Hall to pick up  
the license.

Once we got there Joey and I were swept up in the positive vibe.  All  
the happiness;  surrounded by couples like us who never thought they  
would see this day;  and an efficient, welcoming City administration  
smoothing the way.  It was all wonderful and we became a part of the  
joyful historic moment.  We were married on the balcony at SF City  
Hall feelin' the love of the community we had fought so long and hard  
to help facilitate times like these.

And a legal marriage solves lots of problems like who has the  
authority to decide when to pull the plug when one is on life support  
and fading fast.  Fortunately I executed powers of attorney when we  
first got together, so Joey overruled my doctor who was following my  
instructions ("let me die if it looks like I can't dance again") and  
kept the respirator on.  Now we have clarity on a number of long-term  
relationship issues.

But the important part was looking in his loving eyes while we were  
reciting our vows.

Love,

Apollo






Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

The US is:  "...a nation of 200 million used-car salesmen with all the  
money we need to buy guns and no qualms about killing anybody else in  
the world who tries to make us uncomfortable."
-Hunter S. Thompson

"Friend, hope for the truth while you are alive.  Jump into experience  
while you are alive!  What you call "salvation" belongs to the time  
before death.  If you don't break your ropes while you are alive, do  
you think ghosts will do it after?"
-Kabir





--Boundary_(ID_+MzU+mY3hQPNQ+cOVRwNVQ)--

-Kabir

Our fund-raising gathering is on Friday June 20th @ Sera Phi (2829  
California @ Divisadaro here in San Francisco) to raise monies for a  
community veggie powered diesel generator.... Why? Cause our community  
needs a clean, inexpensive, reliable power source for our community  
gatherings here in California.

On to the line up!
Psychedelic Trance-
Parus :::Live::: (Auraquake/Red Marines)
Liam Shy (Tantra SF)
Goldilox (djgoldilox.com)

RawQUA (Raw Heaven, urmom)

Ben Haus (Acid Totem)
Unityvybe (Acid Totem)
5-MeO  (Acid Totem)

10pm to 6am @ Sera Phi - Bay Area's only 10kw Resonating Dance Floor
2829 California @ Divisadero San Francisco, Ca 94115
www.seraphi.org

Come Hungry! The Sera Phi kitchen will be open and Ananda will be  
making some incredible tasties for your palette's delight. Herbal  
Infused Vodka elixirs and mixed healthy drinks will be available as  
well.

$10 Donation (no guest lists or presales)

It's time for our community to become responsible for our global  
footprint and lessen our impact on our mother earth. Please help us  
make this happen by attending our event or by making a small  
contribution to our Raw Energy project.

((((((Raw Energy)))))) a benefit for a Veggie Powered Generator to

person. ln those transparent moments we know other people's joys and  
sorrows, and we care about their concerns as if they were our own."  -

Hey guys...
I thought I should mention that my electronic disko band, Easystreet, is
playing at Gilman in Berkeley on Saturday night. It's an all ages show,
doors open at 8pm, and we're going on second at 8:40. This is likely to be
our last Bay Area show, so come dance with us before we vaporize! There
might even be candy canes in it for you....

Flyer = www.flickr.com/photos/sexyeasystreet/2578674558/
Easystreet = www.myspace.com/sexyeasystreet

Yay fun!

Love Chelsea

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Connectivate Friday June 27th

Hello all,
Hoping you had a fantastic weekend!  I'm hoping to wrap my head around a 
good way of describing the Stilldream experience of this past weekend, 
but I'm having a little trouble with it right now.  (And yes, as Terri 
mentioned, the space was an amazing one.  There's already some video up 
on SeventhSwami's YouTube page.)  Will get to that when I'm able to 
describe it well.

In the meantime, I want to give everyone a heads up about an upcoming 
event that I'm taking part in; Connectivate.  My understanding is that 
it's the finale, so you should consider experiencing it while you can. 
(But also, one should never say never. ;) )

The Sera Phi building, where the party takes place, will be closing down 
shop and the Connectivate folks are going to be having a grand ole 
blowout to celebrate the occasion.  This last Connectivate will feature 
delicious foods, great music and fun workshops.

*Your Djs for the evening are
*Cumulus (WoM), Chris Sia, Neptune, Deft, Outersect (Outersect.net), Genji,
Dov (Muti Music, Cyberset) Audiovoid (Layers, Muti Music),
Raydeus (Pronoia), Seventh Swami (Ambient Mafia), Beyta,
Niles (MK2Systems) , Unagi (WoM), J.C. (KZSU, AuraSF) and more TBA...

As per usual there will be 2 rooms of sound to tickle your guts, including
one room with 14 subwoofers built into the floor.

Delicious foods will be served up by The Sera Lounge: 
http://www.seralounge.com

Please come join us as we say good bye to this unique space.

Connectivate
Friday June 27th
9pm- 6am
$10 General $15 with Workshop
2829 California St
San Francisco, CA 94115



-- 
San Francisco Bay Guardian's Readers Choice Award Winner: Best Radio DJ:
http://www.sfbg.com/promo/pollpositions.php
AIM: jckzsu (or kzsudj during my show.)

"Opinions are my own only, and do not necessarily represent those of

on the net.

Such a breathtaking sunset on Ocean Beach tonight.  

 

 

 

MySpace:   <http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo> http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet:    <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>
http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k                  
House Music 101:   <http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm>
http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"An adult is one who has lost the grace, the freshness, the innocence of the
child, who is no longer capable of feeling pure joy, who makes everything
complicated, who spreads suffering everywhere, who is afraid of being happy,
and who, because it is easier to bear, has gone back to sleep.  The wise man
is a happy child."
-Arnaud Desjardins

"Music rots when it gets too far from the dance.  Poetry atrophies when it
gets too far from the music."
-Ezra Pound

Tonight's Radio Integrated will be our last show broadcasting live from the
Bliss Factory in Alameda, before our one month recess. During our break
we're going to be doing a little revamp of Radio Integrated, but we'll be
back in August, bigger, better, and more shiny! Tune in at http://radio
.defsf.com:1200/ tonight from 9pm-1am, or feel free to swing by the Bliss
Factory with some Red Stripe if you know where we're at.  ;)

*Featuring DJs:
Paul Leath (DoBox)  -> **http://www.myspace.com/paulleath :
http://doboxrecordings.com**Paul Leath has been one of the innovators of the
Southbay techno scene for more than a decade. His style is an infusion of
Techno, DubTech, House and Reggae which melds the cool and groovy with
funky, jackin' techno.

DJ STML (DEF, Radio Integrated)
**A native of South Africa now residing in the Bay, STML is one of our
favorite DJs, cohorts and most awesome collaborators. His always varied sets
are definitions of his vast musical knowledge and exquisite taste. From
bangin' London acid to deep and groovy minimal, STML always holds it down
with style.


Don't miss next week's show, our very last one before our break, live from
Faktion, with DJs Toro Toro, Saya, and Disconnect.

More info and scheduling:
http://www.defsf.com/radiointegrated/integrated


Tune in at :

http://radio.defsf.com:1200/

Tonight from 9pm - 1am Pacific Time

Subject: [sfraves] Two & Four Thanks and Apologies

A big, big, birthday thanks to all of you that came out to Two & Four last night, and an even bigger thanks to those of you who pulled things together to make this happen. It was a hot night in the citaaaaay and I'm sure all of our getting' down heated it up yet another degree or two. ;)



As Chuck mentioned, unfortunately we did get robbed. Four guys off the street came in, hit our door guy and took the cash box. It's really sad when wanting to get your friends and family together for an intimate night of dancing to celebrate your birthday results in a great deal of money lost and a fellow raver getting assaulted. I'm sorry to all of you who had to experience that. For the record, while my empty bank account is definitely feeling the pain, our door guy is mostly okay. He was more shook up by it all than anything else. I'm very thankful that no one else was hurt.

And Chuck, I am very sorry about Hil's and your car. The heat brings out the worst in people sometimes. Best of luck in recovering your things. Please let me know if there's anything I can do to help.

Heart,
Alida




----------MB_8CAA236795B5EDE_14A4_33EB_webmail-nc10.sysops.aol.com--

Subject: [sfraves] WR: Friday Night Adventure

It was kinda hard getting outta the house early 'cause I had sooo many
errands & chores to do... so like I managed to catch the last bus that
went by my house to the main bus stop (The HTC) in Hercules & i ended up
catching the long back roads normal routine bus to BART, but still thought
I had a chance to make it to that Yummy happy hours shindig @ 222 Hyde...

So got to BART, cruised the Freemont trainm transfered, yada yada, got on
the City train @ MAcarthur.. ok... but when teh train hit Mongomery in the
City, train operator announces that everyone had to get out 'cause that
train couldn't travel anymore on that rail & had to reverse to the east
bay route.. Hello 2Day, so I got out & I was kinda urked 'cause it was
already like 9:45 & there was no way I could walk all the way down Market
to Hyde & get a healthy dose of the ear candy, start the evening groovin',
chill with all the Homies time, so I just got a burger @ McD's & took my
time getting to desintation grrove spot 2: Anu!!!

So like 10:30ish I got to Grime City & all i gotta say about the next few
hours there... Holy Fuckin' Shit!!!  So opening set was Jungle, dunno who
it was, but Yum... then ok, there was some dubstep goin' on like after
that, but magically it turned into 2 STEP!!!!  Holy shit... so for the
next hour, I was in HEAVEN!!!  Yeah... it was all 2 Step & Bassline
stuff... so Dope!!!  Then Subtek busted out a dubstep set, but when Jammin
got back on the decks again... lol... she hella played more Bassline yummy
stuff  before she went back into more dubstep, but man,  I was floored
'cause it was just sooo damn Dope to have that much 2 Step to dance to in
a really long time!

The headlining DJ was this dude from NYC, ummm, CAptain Gelatin ummm, no
no no wait... ooooooooh, Secret Agent Gel!!!  But yeah... he was sick.. I
mean.. he mixed everything from Old Skool Hip Hop, to Breaks, & Dubstep,
even some Lionel Richie!  LoL.. no seriously!!  LoL

It was a good crowd too.. everyone there was all about the music & we kept
that dance floor packed the whole night, esp during the 2 Step ;) !  It
was also Dope seein' all my Dub Step Familia there & just kickin' it w/
the crew again!  The funniest part of the night was when we were all
outside kickin' it & this bum wearin' a motorcycle helmet was blowing a
whistle to signal passing cars to go into his parking slot on the street..
at the same time, 2 decked out vans drive by with ThizzLatino Crew all
painted all fancy on the side door, so I yell "Aye, I want me E, where the
fuck's my E ThizzLatino". then like seconds after i yelled that, a cop
pulls over & starts askin' the bum w/ the motorcycle helmet what drugs he
was on, the bum in the helmet starts yelling @ the bum sleeping on the
sidewalk, 8 more cops show up, it was funny as fuck!

After that I was reeeeeally fortunate to get a ride to the Mission to hang
out for a bit w/ my Homies Cris & Laura @ their pad & catch a cab from
there to Gingerbread 'cause it was cheaper.. after an almost drink & a
cuddle w/ 1 of their cats... had an interesting cab there ride & finally,
made it!!!  YAAAAAAAY... it was time to celebrate w/ my Car singing fairy
raver Princess ;)

When i got over there, like i mean.. it took a looooooooooooong looong
time for me to mentally & physically like transition myself to the house
music & enviorment of people.  I mean... like the house crowd has changed
alot in the past couple years & there's alot thugs now, shiney snobby
people, like well.. yeah, & like on the rare occasion i go to an all house
shindig... I just noticed it changed alot...

It was funny, like right when i got there, I saw M3 & he looked at me &
said "What Fuckin' Hell? Where you been stranger?" & we gave each other
this mondo hug.. Lol... then i wished him happy birthday for the past 6
birthdays i missed... I mean.. aside from the vato thugs & snobs, there
were still alota old skool rave troopers there & a whole bunch of Family!

I did dance a lil when M3 spun, he played some r3eally good tunes, oh oh
oh oh oh oh, & Lida had a man w/ a big Penis cake.. that was sweet... by
the last set, Andrew, like it was all about the hardcore ravers left on
the floor & I did feel more comfort FINALLY.. but it wasn't until
literally, the last 15  minutes, when well... me & this Girl, Amazing
dancer, & I were like havin' a step battle kinda 'cause she had some
smooth ass moves & well.. it wasn't really a battle, but we were just
dancing' together & double steppin & triple steppin' to Andrew! :)

I mean.. despite all the yucky bad that happened @ Lida's bday shindig, it
still was a good night for alota people, it served a great need for some
dance floor action, & well.. whatever existhing good energy there was
there!!  Alot people were happy & I saw that & it was a special time. I
mean.. yeah.. there were so many etards & it was fun getting the random
hugs from them ;)  YAAAAY!!!

It was touching, like the moments I got my own personal Lida time w/ her &
it was just Awesome talkin' again with her!  I mean... we always have alot
to talk about & we reminised alot & I had to do my "OH MYGOSH, HELLO 2DAY"
impersonation of her :)

OK Sweetie, Happy Really Hardcore Birthday today!!! {{{HUGZ}}}

YAAAAY.. good times!!!

oooh... but like i'm sad for what happen to ya Hil & Chuckie.. I'm just
glad y'all safe & in 1 piece!

Good to see everyone else from here who i saw!!
-- 
Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> O§bY {8O)

Damn Chuck sorry to hear you and some of the others on this list were victi=
ms of crimes this weekend! Sounds like the party aspect went down HARD! Alt=
hough it is disturbing because early Friday evening I stopped at a parking =
lot with my friend to blaze a bowl on Harrison before happy hour and saw th=
ese two guys taxing everyone=92s door handles on cars in the parking lot lo=
oking for an opened vehicle. Eventually the two guys saw us and tried to pl=
ay it off and they walked down the street leaving the parking lot.=20
=20
Maybe the heat brought out the worst in people this past weekend=85 The onl=
y thing is you never know anyone can have their car broken into anywhere ev=
en nice rich areas=85However, sometimes it is better to just drive a little=
 longer looking for a more secure spot or just pay money to have your car s=
ecured in a parking lot. My car sticks out like a sore thumb so I hit up th=
e secured parking lots in SF and tend to miss certain events because of it.=
 Not the best for my agenda but when I was 16 back in the day I did not giv=
e a fuck and now I do.
=20
I remember one time walking with peeps on Folsom near the 101 overpass late=
 at night and seeing these three people with one girl crying but obviously =
intoxicated drama crying and her boyfriend consoling her and you could see =
glass everywhere near the passenger side of the car on the street. The girl=
=92s boyfriend asked us if we saw anybody that looked suspicious and we did=
 not and the girl was screaming "these fuckers pissed in my car and now my =
car smells like pee and my things are missing" it was sad. Ever since then =
I became a believer in watching where I put my goods and how much cash I ha=
ve with me on the street.=20
=20
Just like it is cool to feel bad or give a few bucks once in a while to a h=
omeless guy walking by or someone down on their luck but watch out because =
you never know who you are dealing with and what their motives or intention=
s are (e.g., Market Street hustle capital). You never know what that person=
=92s mental capacity is at that time or their mental state.=20

Sad because a lot of thugs/homeless people are mentally ill and need help t=
hat the system can not provide. Believe me if you just walk on by minding y=
our own business and they are trying to engage you in conversation it does =
not make you an evil person for ignoring someone that looks like they may b=
e trouble. Working in the legal field I have read many weird cases that sou=
nd like fantasy! People are people and will do it=85=20
=20
The downside is I feel compelled to avoid having my car broken into so I us=
ually stay away from certain areas in SF when partying. Many undergrounds o=
r parties take place in areas outside my little secure ring of areas of whe=
re I stash my vehicle and take taxi cabs so I tend to stay away. It sucks a=
nd it is not the fault of the people throwing the parties because they can =
not provide absolute security (e.g., can the U.S. secure every neighborhood=
 in Baghdad with billions of $$$ not happening).=20

It is to much to ask any bar owner or promoter of a gig but when I stumbled=
 across the directions to the Gingerbread event I thought about that hood o=
f projects up on the hill that is visible from the 280 on Potrero Hill and =
all the street gangs on that corner of the outer Mission and I was like no =
way my car and a few pot sessions makes it through the night without someon=
e looking for trouble. It is one thing to think you are urban and another t=
o just flat out be in the wrong place at the wrong time, shit happens. I li=
ke to take breaks and smoke at events before going back into the bar and sm=
oke bud while playing DVD=92s or listen to Area 33 in my car so some place =
off the beaten path in someone else=92s hood seemed a little bit to dangero=
us.

thought I'd put out the call to SFRaves, if anyone knows the person.  =20

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Jovino returns to An Epiphany Of Sound this Thursday

I'm hoping that you all had a chance to catch Jovino when he made an 
appearance on An Epiphany Of Sound a month ago.  He provided a HUGE 
dose of BIG Electro House sounds for those that tuned in.  It was truly 
impressive, and truly a fantastic way to begin a Thursday morning.

Well, he'll be back again this Thursday.  So if you missed him last 
month, nows your chance to check him out.  And if you caught him last 
month, you know you won't want to sleep on another chance to listen in.

He'll also be appearing in the Castro the weekend for Pink Saturday (in 
front of the Bank of America (aka Bank Of Apartheid).)  So be sure to 
put that on your calendar too.

A little more about Jovino:
Currently, he's the resident for Nerd Salon, and he's been a guest DJ in 
clubs such as The Fencesitter's Ball and most recently F*ck S4it Let's 
Dance (FSLD).  He also has a regular show on Theory Radio 
(http://theoryradio.org/) every Wednesday from 12-noon to 2pm.

Listen in this Thursday on 90.1 FM in the Bay Area, as well as online at 
http://kzsulive.stanford.edu .

P.S., for those of you who are interested in the behind the scenes 
aspects of college radio, KZSU will be holding it's Informational 
Meeting this coming Monday, June 30th.  That's where you can find out 
all about what takes place behind the scenes and see if there might be a 
spot where you would fit in that puzzle.

JUNE 30, 2008
7 PM
In the KZSU NewsRoom

Located in the Basement of Memorial Auditorium
http://kzsu.stanford.edu/internal/publicity/summerinfo1.doc
http://kzsu.stanford.edu/internal/publicity/summerinfo2.doc
http://kzsu.stanford.edu/internal/publicity/summerinfo3.doc

Be happy.

Subject: [sfraves] Acid mix from Jeno on Qpod, special event broadcast for Return 2 Acid

------=_Part_170_17669315.1214283533430
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable
Content-Disposition: inline

Jeno has been kind enough to put together an old school set of house and
acid as a special event broadcast for Return 2 Acid (this friday 6.27.08 @
Radiance factory) for Qpod.  Enjoy, and feel free to browse the site and
give the other pods a listen!

http://qpod.org/2008/06/23/qpod-special-event-broadcast--62708-return-2-aci=
d--dj-jeno-2.aspx

For this special event broadcast, we have none other than Jeno from the
infamous Wicked Crew that started full moon madness in the states.  While
Wicked has long been dead, the anarchic nights spent at places like Bonny
Doon Beach still resonate with those who were lucky enough to have partaken
in the Wicked Full Moon experience. Jeno, along with his fellow Wicked
comrades played an integral role in introducing the acid house sounds of th=
e
UK to the West Coast.  Nowdays, you can catch Jeno every Tuesday night on
his weekly internet broadcast on ,
NoisefromtheVoid<http://noisefromthevoid.com/>.
He has also teamed up with Wicked alumni and Grayhound Records label honcho=
,
DJ Garth, for a party called Back 2 Back at 222 Hyde in San Francisco.  The
party features the enlightening sounds of disco-electronica from deep withi=
n
both Jeno's and Garth's record libraries.

Jeno has been kind enough to share a mix of old school acid and rave
classics for this special broadcast on Qpod.  We hope you enjoy the acidy
goodness in your headphones, and one more time with your friends from Qpod
and Acid Totem this friday at Return 2 Acid!


Tracklist:

1.   Da Rebels - For U
2.   Centerfield Assignment - Mi Casa
3.   The Moody Boyz -King of the Funky Zulus
4.   Diceman - Quad
5.   KC Flight - Planet E
6.   The H-Men - Scream (dub mix)
7.   The H-Men - Scream (radio mix)
8.   Farley - The Acid Life
9.   L N R - Work it to the Bone (dub)
10. Fast Eddie - The Nite Life
11. Risqu=E9 Rhythm Team - More Than Just a Dance
12. E-Zee Posse - The Sun Machine
13. Caucasian Boy - Gone Clear
14. Frequency X - I shot Him (unforgettable mix)
15. The Daou - Surrender Yourself
16. System 7 - Sunburst
17. Mory Kante - Ye Ke Ye Ke (afro acid mix)
18. 808 State - Flowcoma

Bubble machines aren't that expensive - you can get one for $30 or so at a
party store, so I would just buy one.  My bubble machine is broken, so I'm
bubble-less right now, but it's a nice thing to have around, it adds a
couple fun points and maybe one "WTF?" point to any occasion. I've had my
eye on this bubble machine called the "Jumbubbler", which makes bubbles
bigger than your head.  Sweet!!
-CH

Hi Everyone!

It's my birfday soon and as always that means it's time for some dancin'!
Please come out and shake yer bootay in honor of me being around! Yay. I'm a
fond fond lover of the deep funky house music, and so me and my homie Eric
Sharp came up with a list of DJs guaranteed to bring that sweet sound to
your ears to keep you moving all night long.

Hope to see all the old skool kids on the floor tearin it up like we used to
do!

Cheers,
Katie (KT-Mow)

+++

Rock It Science presents:
Take Me Back To Your House!
Saturday, June 28
10 PM - Very late

~An old school underground house music event!!~

We invite you to remember the first time you stepped on the dancefloor and
completely lost yourself in the relentless pounding of the beat.  Please
join us as we take you back with great music, friends, and a dance floor
that will not quit!

Homero Espinosa (Yerba Buena Discos)
Eric Sharp (Rock It Science)
Jimmy B (Green Gorilla Lounge)
Native Intelligence (Rock It Science)
Mario Dubbz (Movement, Essential Nightlife)

Happy Birthday KT!!

21 +
San Francisco Location TBA the night of the party
Info Line: 888 482 9281

~$5 before 11, $10 before 12am, $15 after~
